I"¯[<p>The score function is the gradient of the log-density. As a unique way to represent probability distributions, score functions have enabled the development of many computationally efficient tools for machine learning and statistics, collectively known as score-based methods. By working with distributions through score functions, they have found widespread applications in vastly disjointed subfields of machine learning and statistics.</p>

<p>The impact of score-based methods in each of these fields has been significant. For example, generative models based on score functions, known as score-based generative models or denoising diffusion models, allow the generation of very high quality and diverse data, emerging as the new state-of-the-art technique in applications such as text-to-image generation, video generation, audio synthesis, and point cloud generation. Developments on Steinâ€™s method and score-based approaches for SDEs have also advanced fast and robust Bayesian posterior inference in high dimensions, with applications to improving simulation models in engineering fields.</p>

<p>Through this workshop, we aim to</p>
<ul>
  <li>Bring together researchers from a wide range of subfields to initiate a broad discussion on what makes score-based methods so successful, and what common challenges are faced across seemingly different areas of research;</li>
  <li>Explore the potential of score-based methods to a wide range of relevant real-world applications, such as those in computer vision, signal processing, computational chemistry, and other disciplines of science and engineering.</li>
</ul>

<p>By doing so, we hope to facilitate synergy across score-based methods in different fields, identify unexplored areas that can benefit from insights into these methods, and provide the foundations for the development of a more coherent research community focused on tackling the challenges of score-based methods.</p>

<p>This workshop will be an <strong>in-person event</strong> at <a href="https://neurips.cc/">NeurIPS 2022</a>, taking place on <strong>Dec 2nd 2022 (tentative)</strong>. The session will cover invited talks, contributed talks and posters.</p>

<h1 id="key-dates">key dates</h1>

<ul>
  <li>
    <p>Submission deadline: <strong>22 Sept 2022 (11:59 pm AOE)</strong></p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>Acceptance notification: <strong>Oct 20, 2022</strong></p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>Camera ready for accepted submissions: <strong>Nov 25, 2022</strong></p>
  </li>
</ul>

